font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, it would be a clear violation of the UK’s international legal obligations were the Government and Parliament to refuse to comply with the Hirst judgment.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> See also the JCHR’s reports</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> referred to in my written evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It is also important to have regard to the UK’s international obligations as party to the UN International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Article 25 of the ICCPR</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> protects the right and opportunity of every citizen, subject to reasonable restrictions, to vote and to be elected at genuine periodic election by universal and equal suffrage. Article 2.2 obliges the parties to adopt necessary legislative measures to give effect to the IPPR protected rights.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The UK ratified the ICCPR in 1976 without making any relevant declaration or reservation in relation to Article 25.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Do you agree with Jonathan Fisher QC in his argument that “an international treaty binds a State, not its Government nor its ministers”?  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Is it relevant that whilst Article 46 ... requires the UK to abide by the final decision of the Strasbourg court ... Article 46 was not incorporated into domestic law when the Human Rights Act was passed?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">No.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> . The obligation imposed by Article 46 (1) is an international legal obligation.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> State responsibility for complying </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">with the Convention involves all</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> three branches of government, executive, legislative and judicial and the other public authorities of the United Kingdom and its countries and regions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It is ir</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">relevant that Article 46 was not inco</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rporated. M</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ost provisions of the Convention other than the Convention rights and freedoms</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> were not incorporated because they are unnecessary to give effect to t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ose rights and freedoms in domestic law.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Ministerial</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Code describes Ministers as having an overarching duty to comply with the law including international law and t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">reaty obligations. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he Government confirmed in a Written Answer by Lord </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">McNally on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 June 2013 (WA 160) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> that there are o current plans to amend paragraph 1.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> in light of the HIrst case</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> .</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In an article in the Telegraph, it is claimed that you compare the current impasse between the UK Government and the European Court of Human Rights to the situation in Greece under the junta.  Do you think this is a fair comparison? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Is it reasonable that the UK Government is coming under such criticism considering the number of violations other countries have committed? </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">How might it affect the attitude and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">behaviour of other countries who</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are also in breach of international human rights law?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">My</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> reference to Greece</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">’s withdrawal from the Council of Europe </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">under the junta was</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> intended</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to draw attention to the fact that if the UK were to refuse to compl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">y with it</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">duty to abide by the Court’s final judgments against the UK, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">we would </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">too </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">be compelled </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to withdraw from the Convention system rather than face expulsion.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> It was not of course intended to suggest that our political circumstances are similar to those in Greece under the junta.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The UK has had an unblemished record of complying with judgments of the Strasbourg Court until now a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">nd of upholding the European rul</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e of law. Other states have dragged their feet in complying with judgments, but I know of no example of a state refusing to comply with Article 46.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> The UK prides itself on being a rule of law country and it is reasonable that successive Governments have been strongly criticised for their failure to comply with Article 46.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The fact that other states violate Convention rights is irrelevant</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to the obligations of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> UK as a Contracting Party</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">What does the current dispute with the Strasbourg court mean for the constitutional principle of the Sovereignty of Parliament? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Human Rights Act gives effect to Parliamentary sovereignty by preventing our courts from striki</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ng down Acts of Parliament. If </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">primary legislation cannot be read and given effect compatibly with the Convention rights, the courts may grant a declaration of incompatibility leaving its to government and Parliament to decide whether to take remedial action.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The fact that Parliament </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">has exclusiv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e responsibility to make the law</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> does not affect the State’s responsibility to comply with rulings of the European Court of Human Rights : eg., in the East African Asians case</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (1973) 3 EHRR 76</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">However the Strasbourg Court and the Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe in its</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> supervisory capacity, recognise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> a wide area of discretionary judgment for the legislature in choosing the means of complying.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Martin Howe QC has suggested, in written evidence to this Committee, that the UK should withdraw from the First Protocol to the Convention, and notes that Switzerland, a member of the Council of Europe, has never ratified the Protocol. Is this a feasible option?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Human Rights Act would then have to be amended to remove protection of the Convention</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> rights to private property, education and political freedom. It would be an odd decision for a Conservative government to take since it was a Conservative Government th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">at ratified the First Protocol.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> And it would undermine the basic c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ivil rights and libertie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s of our fellow citizens</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Unlike Switzerland and every other State party to the Convention, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the UK does not have a written constitution protecting fundamental human rights.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> It was only in 1990, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">after Switze</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">la</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">nd had ratified the Convention,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Swiss </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">women were given the right to vote in every canton. The Convention was the crucial lever</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> for women’s enfranchisement.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Anthony Speaight QC has argued, in evidence to this committee, that the Strasbourg Court has ignored the intentions of the drafters of the First Protocol in its judgments on prisoner voting. Do you agree? Why was a clearly defined right to vote not included in the Convention if this was the intention of its drafters?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">I do not agree. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">There were no such intention</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and it was </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">obvious that the right to vote was inherent in Article 3.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Churchill</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Government signed and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ratifi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ed Protocol No. 1 in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">1952</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> on behalf of the UK </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">without making any reservation or declaration in relation to Article 3.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It was unnecessary </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the drafters of Article 3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to make explicit reference to the right to vote since it is inherent in the very concept of a modern democratic society in which the people choose their legislature in a secret ballot</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">I do not understand how free elections could be held under conditions ensuring the free expression of the opinion of the people in the choice of the legislature without the right to vote.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Strasbourg Court’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> interpretation of Article 3 was first explained 25 years ago in Mathieu-Mohin and Clerfayt v Belgium (1987) 10 EHRR 1, paragraphs 46-54, and was not controversial or objected to by our government. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> The British judge on the Court, Sir Vincent Evans, was former Legal Adviser to the Foreign Office. The Court agreed with the approach of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the Euro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">pean Commission of Human Rights which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">observed in that case, “Universal suffrage, the central element of any </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">genuinely democratic political system, must seek to ensure ‘the free expression of the opinion of the people in the choice of the legislature.’”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Suppose </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">hypothetically </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">that only men or only white people were e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ntitled to vote in P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> elections</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to the legislature, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">or that Jews were excluded</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. It is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">obvious that this would engage Article 3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">of the First Protocol.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> For example in Aziz v Cyprus (2008) 46 EHRRv39, the Court found a violation of article 3 where members of the Turkish-Cypriot community living in the government-controlled area of Cyprus were refused permission to be included on the electoral r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">oll; or Sejdic and Finci v Bosnia and Herzeg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ovina (Grand Chamber 2009) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">where Roma and Jews were excluded under the Constitution from being elected to the legislature</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties contains general principles for the interpretation of treaties.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Article 31.1 provides that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“A treaty shall be interpreted in good faith in accordance with the ordinary meaning to be given to the terms of the treaty in their context and in the light of its object and purpose.”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Under the heading “Supplementary means of interpretation, Article 32 provides that </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Recourse may be had to supplementary means of interpretation, including the preparatory work of the treaty and the circumstances of its</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> conclusi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">on, in order to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">confirm the meaning</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> resulting from the application of Article 31, or to determine the meaning when the application of Article 31: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">leaves the meaning ambiguous or obscure; or</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">leads to a result which is manifestly absurd or unreasonable.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Preparatory work does not have the same authentic character as Article 31 “ Brownlie, Principles of Public International Law (7</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> ed., 2005), 632.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">That is the approach of our own courts in deciding whether to have recourse to parliamentary debates or other extrinsic material to interpret</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> primary legislation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">: Pepper v Hart</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">[1992] UKHL 3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> . It is supplemental and exceptional</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Our courts also use an updating approach to statutory interpretation, rather than being tied to an inflexible approach that is tied to the original intention of the legislature.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">: Bennion on Statutory Interp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">etation (5</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> ed., </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> 2008), section 288,  889-914: Presumption that updating construction to be given.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he preparatory work </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">referred to by Anthony Speaight QC and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Dominic Raab MP is not relevan</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to the intention</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> of the drafters of Article 3. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Mr Raab refers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to objections made by the Attlee Government to include in the Convention what became Article 3 of Protocol No. 1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It was when the Churchill government came to power that Protocol. No. 1 was agreed, and there is nothing in the preparatory work on Protocol No. 1 to indicate any intention to exclude the right to vote in elections for the choice of legislature. Th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> main UK concern was to protect</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the unelected nature of the House of Lords</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> from being held to be contrary to Article 3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">What restrictions on the right to vote (if any) do you think it is legitimate to place on prisoners?</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Is it reasonable to restrict the right to vote of those convicted of electoral offences, terrorism or other offences designed to have an impact on the democratic process?</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It would be within the wide area of discretionary judgment allowed to government and Parliament</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. Cyprus, Ireland and Hong Kong have n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ot found it necessary so to impose such rstrictions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">any</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of the options contained in the draft Voting Eligibility (Prisoners) Bill a long-term solution to the issue of prisoner voting, or is it just matter of time before Strasbourg case-law develops still further?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The test to be satisfied will remain the test of proportionality. The Court will continue to recognise a wide margin of appreciation in this area, especially if Parliament has carefully considered</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the options and come to a well-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">informed conclusion</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> that is not manifestly unreasonable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li styl